city.cs.engine

Class World

  • java.lang.Object
    • city.cs.engine.World

  • public class World
extends Object
    A world in which the motion and interaction of a number of rigid bodies is simulated. Bodies are added to the world automatically when they are created.

    Quantities in the world are measured using the SI system (metres, kilograms and seconds):

    • Displacements and velocities in the world are represented using the Vec2 class. A Vec2 has an x-component (increases to the right) and a y-component (increases upwards).
    • Angles are measured in radians; to convert degrees to radians, divide by MathUtils.RAD2DEG; to convert radians to degrees, multiply by MathUtils.RAD2DEG.

    Once started, the simulation approximates physical behaviour by computing positions and velocities of bodies at discrete time steps (by default, 1/60 of a second). StepListeners can be registered to invoke application code immediately before and after each simulation step. Once started, the simulation can be stopped and resumed.

    Warning: When the simulation is running, the world should only be modified from the AWT thread, i.e. using the listener interfaces of this library, the AWT and Swing. In particular, all initialization must be complete before the world is started.

    See Also:
    Body.addCollisionListener(city.cs.engine.CollisionListener), Sensor.addSensorListener(city.cs.engine.SensorListener)

      • stop

        public void stop()
        Stop the simulation. When stopped, the simulation may be advanced one step at a time using oneStep(), or resumed with start().

        If stop() is called during a call to preStep(), the simulation step will not take place.

      • setGravity

        public void setGravity(float g)
        Set the strength of gravity in this world. The new gravity acceleration vector will act vertically downwards with the specified strength. Setting negative gravity strength causes gravity to act upwards instead of downwards. Note that individual bodies have their own gravity scale attribute (default 1.0f) which is multiplied with the global gravity strength when simulating the effect of gravity on bodies.
        Parameters:
        g - the new gravity strength in metres per second per second
        See Also:
        DynamicBody.setGravityScale(float)

      • addStepListener

        public void addStepListener(StepListener listener)
        Register a listener to be notified before and after each simulation step. The listener's preStep() method is called immediately before each simulation step. The listener's postStep() method is called immediately after each simulation step. The postStep() methods are called the simulation step has finished and collision listeners have been called.
        Parameters:
        listener - the listener to add
        See Also:
        addChangeListener(javax.swing.event.ChangeListener)
